layout: post
title: Very Old Void System Updates
date: 2017-09-24 18:00:00
categories: Void XBPS Update
---

I have a lot of computers in my collection from machines I've wanted
or otherwise picked up over the years.  Some of these machines were
aquired as projects and spend a lot of time in the off state.  One of
my oldest Void machines has been off for around 2 years now.  With
October fast approaching I decided I wanted to try and project a
halloween scene into my window.  I had the projector already along
with some video clips that would work for this.  The tripod and the
rear projection material are readily obtained from Amazon, and all
that left was a computer to run the videos.  I dug out an Eee 701 from
my collection and it is what I will use, but it needs to be updated
first.


When did I last boot this system?  Hmm, no date here.  Fortunately
there's a file from a talk I gave that is the final edited copy and I
know that is the last time I booted the machine.  Since I have the
year from that talk I know that the last time this machine booted was
Sunday December 20th, 2015.  It has not been updated or modified since
shutting down at 10:46PM that night, if I remember, I shut it down
because my food had arived at an IHOP resturant after the talk.

```
$ last -x | head -n2
maldridg tty1                          Sun Sep 24 19:28   still logged in
maldridg tty1                          Sun Dec 20 21:18 - 10:46 (17+13:27)
```

What repos was this using?  I think that predates the utdlug mirror...
```
$ cat /etc/xbps.d/*
repository=http://repo3.voidlinux.eu/current
repository=http://repo.voidlinux.eu/current
repository=http://repo3.voidlinux.eu/current/nonfree
repository=http://repo.voidlinux.eu/current/nonfree
```

Why are there two of everything?

```
$ ls /etc/xbps.d/
00-repository-main.conf
00-repository-main.conf~
10-repository-nonfree.conf
10-repository-nonfree.conf~
```

Oh, because I didn't emacs right and this doesn't have my updated
dotfiles on it.  Easy enough to change.

```
$ sudo rm /etc/xbps.d/*~
$ ls /etc/xbps.d/
/etc/xbps.d/00-repository-main.conf
/etc/xbps.d/10-repository-nonfree.conf
```

Okay, are we down to the right number of mirrors again?

```
$ cat /etc/xbps.d/*
repository=http://repo3.voidlinux.eu/current
repository=http://repo3.voidlinux.eu/current/nonfree
```

Yes, but they're the wrong mirrors, lets reset those.

```
$ sudo sed -i "s:repo3.voidlinux.eu:lug.utdallas.edu/mirror/void:g" /etc/xbps.d/*
$ cat /etc/xbps.d/*
repository=http://lug.utdallas.edu/mirror/void/current
repository=http://lug.utdallas.edu/mirror/void/current/nonfree
```

Cool, so its pointing at the right mirrors now, the question is if
this is going to talk to the mirror at all since the SSL certificates
are probably long out of date.

```
$ sudo xbps-install -S
```

Something that many users havn't seen since xbps is infrequently
updated is that it does not update everything in one pass if it has an
update for itself pending.  The first pass above updated XBPS itself
and its core binaries, so now we'll run another update to bring the
system up to date.

Wow that was a lot of updates running all at once.  For those playing
along at home, yes that was pretty much a full system re-install
happening with the system online.


Having run the update I'm feeling confident, lets go for broke and
reboot.

```
$ sudo reboot
```

Yep, now running the latest kernel.

```
$ uname -a
Linux europa 4.12.13_1 #1 SMP PREEMPT Thu Sep 14 13:15:00 UTC 2017 i686 GNU/Linux
```

Everything came up fine, but in 2 years I've changed a lot of
workflows so virtually none of my GUI configuration was usable (I no
longer use awesomewm).  Given that the system is updated though, I can
now clean it up and remove the packages I no longer use.

Its still pretty cool though to see that you can actually update a Void
install from 2 years ago.
